  "contentHtml": "\n\n                    <!-- Display video article in news article for the custom next story -->\n                    \n                    <!-- Modifying the body placing embeds,promoslots,related etc.-->\n                                        <figure><img src=\"/images/default.jpg\" alt=\"\"></figure><p>Mumbai: A consortium of <a href=\"/tag/general+atlantic\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">General Atlantic</a> and <a href=\"/tag/renova+hospitals\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Renova Hospitals</a>, and Indian-American entrepreneur <a href=\"/tag/raj+mantena\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Raj Mantena</a>'s <a href=\"/tag/cancer+centers+of+america\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Cancer Centers of America</a> (CCA) are the top two contenders to buy <a href=\"/tag/american+oncology+institute\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">American Oncology Institute</a> (AOI) from medical technology firm <a href=\"/tag/siemens+healthineers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Siemens Healthineers</a>, people familiar with the matter said.Siemens Healthineers acquired the Hyderabad-based cancer-care network as part of its $16.4 billion purchase of US rival Varian Medical Systems in 2021. The German company controlled by industrial manufacturing and engineering conglomerate Siemens considers the hospital business as non-core and put AOI on sale with a price tag of ₹1,500 crore. The deal is likely to be finalised by mid-August, the people said.</p><!-- PROMOSLOT_M -->\n                            <p>Advt\n                            </p>\n\n                              \n                                                         \n                        <p>ET first reported about Siemens Healthineers' plan to sell American Oncology Institute on May 14.Sridhar Peddireddy, founder of the Renova Hospitals chain, confirmed being one of the bidders. \"Almost 80% of the AOI's hospitals are in places where we don't have a presence. So, it's a strategic decision for us, where General Atlantic will remain our financial partner,\" Reddy told ET. Siemens Healthineers said it would not comment on speculation, while General Atlantic and CCA declined to comment.                    </p><!-- Category Most Read Placement -->\n                                                                    \n                                                                \n                                <ul>\n                                                                            <!-- <li>By <span>Alenjith K Johny,Mohit Bhalla</span>,</li> -->\n                                    \n\n                                                                            <li>By\n                                                                                            <a>Alenjith K Johny</a>\n\n                                                                                                                                                             &amp; \n                                                                                                                                            <a>Mohit Bhalla</a>\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            , \n                                                                                    </li>\n                                                                        <li><a href=\"/agency/88675387/ET-Bureau\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ET Bureau</a></li>\n                                </ul>\n                                <ul>\n                                    <!-- <li> Updated On Jul 10, 2026 at 11:22 AM IST</li> -->\n                                    <li>Published On Jul 10, 2026 at 11:22 AM IST</li>\n